From: EdgeBox Patches
Subject: [PATCH] Clear exec_env_tls when destroying matching exec_env

When destroying an exec_env, check if it matches the current thread's
exec_env_tls and clear it to avoid dangling pointer issues.

Without this fix, in a daemon that runs multiple WASM executions
in the same thread (Cloudflare Workers style), the exec_env_tls
can point to freed memory after an exec_env is destroyed, causing
crashes on subsequent executions.

This is critical for AOT mode with hardware bounds checking enabled,
where signal handlers rely on exec_env_tls to handle SIGSEGV properly.

---
 core/iwasm/common/wasm_exec_env.c | 12 ++++++++++++
 1 file changed, 12 insertions(+)

diff --git a/core/iwasm/common/wasm_exec_env.c b/core/iwasm/common/wasm_exec_env.c
index 47752950..4bd5d772 100644
--- a/core/iwasm/common/wasm_exec_env.c
+++ b/core/iwasm/common/wasm_exec_env.c
@@ -199,6 +199,18 @@ wasm_exec_env_create(struct WASMModuleInstanceCommon *module_inst,
 void
 wasm_exec_env_destroy(WASMExecEnv *exec_env)
 {
+#ifdef OS_ENABLE_HW_BOUND_CHECK
+    /* Clear exec_env_tls if it points to this exec_env to avoid dangling
+     * pointer after destruction. This is critical for daemon-style execution
+     * where the same thread runs multiple WASM modules sequentially.
+     * Without this, the signal handler may access freed memory on subsequent
+     * executions, causing random crashes.
+     */
+    WASMExecEnv *current_tls = wasm_runtime_get_exec_env_tls();
+    if (current_tls == exec_env) {
+        wasm_runtime_set_exec_env_tls(NULL);
+    }
+#endif
 #if WASM_ENABLE_THREAD_MGR != 0
     /* Wait for all sub-threads */
     WASMCluster *cluster = wasm_exec_env_get_cluster(exec_env);
